# Token economy

Bias toward fewer, smaller, cheaper model calls without losing quality. For trivial
one-shot edits the overhead isn't worth it — use judgment.

## In-session

- **Compact active state.** Keep a short GOAL / CONSTRAINTS / DECISIONS / OPEN / NEXT
  block and update it instead of re-deriving context from history.
- **Recent context only.** Collapse finished sub-tasks to a one-line outcome; drop stale
  tool output and abandoned plans.
- **Only necessary files.** Read the minimum — targeted search + a small slice beats
  whole files. Don't attach files you won't act on.
- **Trim tool outputs.** Keep the 3–5 fields that matter; never feed full logs or JSON
  back into reasoning.
- **Structured outputs, hard limits.** Fixed schemas with explicit caps ("≤ 5 bullets",
  "diff only"). Open-ended answers are a silent token sink.
- **Deterministic code over model calls.** Mechanical transforms (reformat, extract,
  find/replace, count, sort) → a script/one-liner, not token-by-token reasoning.

## Workflow

- New chat per task; carry only the compact state forward.
- Cache stable instructions and schemas; don't re-send the unchanging prefix.
- Retrieval on a strict token budget (top-k + ceiling).
- Route simple steps (classify/extract/short rewrite) to a smaller, cheaper model.
- Split planning, execution, and review into separate chats so each starts lean.
- Measure tokens per workflow, rank by spend, fix the worst offender first.
